Packages & Dataset

Code 
library(tidyverse)
aNames <- read_csv(here::here("Labs", 
                              "Lab09", 
                              "StateNames_A.csv"))

Summarizing & Visualizing the Number of Allisons

Part 1

Code 
aNames <- aNames %>%
  rename(Sex = Gender)
Code 
# https://tidyr.tidyverse.org/reference/replace_na.html: replacing missing values
allisonsSummary <- aNames %>%
  filter(Name == "Allison") %>% 
  group_by(State, Sex) %>%
  summarise(Allisons = sum(Count)) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = Sex, values_from = Allisons) %>%
  replace_na(list(F = 0, M = 0))

Part 2

Code 
allison_f <- aNames  %>% filter(Name == "Allison",
                                Sex == "F")

Part 3

Code 
allison_Years <- allison_f %>% 
  group_by(Year) %>%
  summarise(Allisons = sum(Count))
Code 
# https://www.statology.org/ggplot-background-color/: panel background
allison_Years %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Year, y = Allisons)) +
  geom_line() + 
  labs(title = "Number Of Allisons Throughout 1997 to 2014") +
  theme_linedraw() +
  theme(axis.title.y = element_blank(),
        axis.title.x = element_blank(), 
        plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"), 
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "lightgrey"))

Modeling The Number Of Allisons

Part 1

Code 
allison_lm <- allison_Years %>% 
  lm(Allisons ~ Year, data = .)

Part 2

Code 
broom::tidy(allison_lm)
# A tibble: 2 Ã 5
  term        estimate std.error statistic  p.value
  <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>    <dbl>
1 (Intercept)  209690.   42972.       4.88 0.000167
2 Year           -102.      21.4     -4.74 0.000223
Code 
# Equation = -101.52(Year) + 209689.76

Part 3

There is not really a pattern in the plotted residuals.

Code 
allison_lm %>% broom::augment() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(y = .resid, x = .fitted)) +
  geom_point() + 
  labs(title = "Residual Plot: Number of Babies Named Allison From 1997 to 2014",
       y = "Residuals",
       x = "Fitted") +
  theme_linedraw() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", 
                                  size = 13), 
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "lightgrey"))

The number of babies named Allison has been gradually decreasing since 1997.

Spelling by State

Part 1

Code 
filters <- tibble(Name = c("Allan", "Alan", "Allen"))

als <- aNames %>% semi_join(filters, by = "Name")

Part 2

Code 
al_Years <- als %>%
  group_by(Year, Name) %>%
  summarise(Als = sum(Count))
Code 
al_Years %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Year, y = Als, color = Name)) +
  geom_line() + 
  labs(title = "Number Of Allens, Allans, and Alans Throughout 1997 to 2014") +
  theme_linedraw() +
  theme(axis.title.y = element_blank(),
        axis.title.x = element_blank(), 
        plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "lightgrey"))

Part 3

Code 
al_summary <- als %>% 
  filter(Year == 2000, State %in% c("CA", "PA")) %>%
  group_by(State, Name) %>%
  summarise(Als = sum(Count)) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = Name, values_from = Als)

Part 4

Code 
# https://www.statology.org/dplyr-relocate/: relocate
finalSummary <- al_summary %>% 
  summarise(Total = sum(Allan, Alan, Allen),
            across(.cols = Alan:Allen, .f = ~ round(. / Total, 2))) %>%
  relocate(Total, .after = Allen)

## Packages & Dataset

```{r}
library(tidyverse)
aNames <- read_csv(here::here("Labs", 
                              "Lab09", 
                              "StateNames_A.csv"))
```

## Summarizing & Visualizing the Number of Allisons

Part 1

```{r}
aNames <- aNames %>%
  rename(Sex = Gender)
```

```{r}
# https://tidyr.tidyverse.org/reference/replace_na.html: replacing missing values
allisonsSummary <- aNames %>%
  filter(Name == "Allison") %>% 
  group_by(State, Sex) %>%
  summarise(Allisons = sum(Count)) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = Sex, values_from = Allisons) %>%
  replace_na(list(F = 0, M = 0))
```

Part 2

```{r}
allison_f <- aNames  %>% filter(Name == "Allison",
                                Sex == "F")  
```

Part 3

```{r}
allison_Years <- allison_f %>% 
  group_by(Year) %>%
  summarise(Allisons = sum(Count))
```

```{r}
# https://www.statology.org/ggplot-background-color/: panel background
allison_Years %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Year, y = Allisons)) +
  geom_line() + 
  labs(title = "Number Of Allisons Throughout 1997 to 2014") +
  theme_linedraw() +
  theme(axis.title.y = element_blank(),
        axis.title.x = element_blank(), 
        plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"), 
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "lightgrey"))
```

## Modeling The Number Of Allisons

Part 1

```{r}
allison_lm <- allison_Years %>% 
  lm(Allisons ~ Year, data = .)
```

Part 2

```{r}
broom::tidy(allison_lm)
# Equation = -101.52(Year) + 209689.76
```

Part 3

There is not really a pattern in the plotted residuals.

```{r}
allison_lm %>% broom::augment() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(y = .resid, x = .fitted)) +
  geom_point() + 
  labs(title = "Residual Plot: Number of Babies Named Allison From 1997 to 2014",
       y = "Residuals",
       x = "Fitted") +
  theme_linedraw() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", 
                                  size = 13), 
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "lightgrey"))
```

The number of babies named Allison has been gradually decreasing since 1997.

## Spelling by State

Part 1

```{r}
filters <- tibble(Name = c("Allan", "Alan", "Allen"))

als <- aNames %>% semi_join(filters, by = "Name")
```

Part 2

```{r}
al_Years <- als %>%
  group_by(Year, Name) %>%
  summarise(Als = sum(Count))
```

```{r}
al_Years %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Year, y = Als, color = Name)) +
  geom_line() + 
  labs(title = "Number Of Allens, Allans, and Alans Throughout 1997 to 2014") +
  theme_linedraw() +
  theme(axis.title.y = element_blank(),
        axis.title.x = element_blank(), 
        plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "lightgrey"))
```

Part 3

```{r}
al_summary <- als %>% 
  filter(Year == 2000, State %in% c("CA", "PA")) %>%
  group_by(State, Name) %>%
  summarise(Als = sum(Count)) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = Name, values_from = Als)
```

Part 4

```{r}
# https://www.statology.org/dplyr-relocate/: relocate
finalSummary <- al_summary %>% 
  summarise(Total = sum(Allan, Alan, Allen),
            across(.cols = Alan:Allen, .f = ~ round(. / Total, 2))) %>%
  relocate(Total, .after = Allen)
```
